<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-02-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-02-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="95" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d95">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Conger</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-02-17"><hi rend="italic">February 17,
                                    1904</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1507.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: For the enforcement of the neutrality
                            edict transmitted in my No. 1502, of the 18th instant, the Chinese
                            Government have now published a series of regulations, a copy of which I
                            inclose herewith<note n="a" xml:id="d95fna">Printed under neutrality
                                proclamations, <ref target="#pg_18">p. 18</ref>.</note> and have the
                            honor, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">E. H. Conger.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>